<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1241]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[312,414,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is the most yellow species of 
<taxonomicName box="[861,926,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Pieza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[861,926,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Pieza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known. Some specimens appear orange, but this is probably due to a hypercyanic condition after capture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1241]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[312,435,1095,1120]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet derives from the Latin “ 
<emphasis box="[1001,1029,1095,1120]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">de</emphasis>
” = away from, down + “ 
<emphasis box="[277,378,1135,1160]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">resistens</emphasis>
” = firm, tough; referring to the relative fragility of the only known four female specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[312,1130,1215,1241]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="distribution">
